   <h2><img src="../../images/smart-books.jpg" alt="Module icon" class="right border" width="600"/><i class="mch-compass3"></i> MCH Programs</h2>
   <p>The following is a summary of several key MCH-related programs. </p>
   <h3>Title V Maternal and Child Health Services Block Grant </h3>
   <p><strong>History:</strong> The Title V federal-state partnership was authorized under Title V of the 1935 federal Social Security Act. Title V was converted to a block grant program in 1981 and then was revised in 2015. </p>
   <p><strong>Current Structure: </strong>Title V is one of the largest federal block grant programs. It works to improve the health of all mothers and children, including children and youth with special health care needs (CYSHCN). Focus is on five population domains &mdash; maternal/women&rsquo;s health, perinatal/infant health, child health, adolescent/young adult health, children with special health care needs &mdash; and one capacity domain: cross-cutting/systems-building. Fifteen national performance measures are organized within the five population domains.</p>
   <h3>Medicaid</h3>
   <p><strong>History: </strong>Authorized by Title XIX of the Social Security Act, <a href="https://www.medicaid.gov/medicaid/index.html">Medicaid </a>was signed into law in 1965 alongside Medicare. </p>
   <p><strong>Current Structure: </strong>Medicaid provides health coverage to eligible low-income adults, children, pregnant women, elderly adults, and people with disabilities. Medicaid is administered by states, according to federal requirements. Although the federal government establishes certain parameters for all states to follow, each state administers their Medicaid program differently, resulting in variations in Medicaid coverage across the country.</p>
   <h3>Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP)</h3>
   <p><strong>History: </strong><a href="https://www.medicaid.gov/chip/index.html">CHIP </a>(Title XXI) was signed into law in 1997 and provides federal matching funds to states to provide health coverage to children in families with incomes too high to qualify for Medicaid, but who can't afford private coverage. All states have expanded children's coverage significantly through their CHIP programs, with nearly every state providing coverage for children up to at least 200 percent of the federal poverty level.</p>
<p><strong>Current Structure:</strong> CHIP, unlike Medicaid, is not an entitlement program. Consequently, states may set their own enrollment criteria and program enrollment caps, which causes programs to differ in structure from state to state. </p>
<h3>Healthy Start Initiative</h3>
<p><strong>History: </strong>Healthy Start was created in 1991 as a demonstration project in 15 communities. Today, there are over 100 Healthy Start projects in 37 states and Washington, D.C. </p>
<p><strong>Current Structure: </strong><a href="https://mchb.hrsa.gov/maternal-child-health-initiatives/healthy-start">Healthy Start</a> works at the community, state, and national levels to improve health outcomes before, during, and after pregnancy, and reduces racial/ethnic differences in the rates of infant death and adverse perinatal outcomes.  </p>
<h3>Emergency Medical Services for Children Program</h3>
<p><strong>History: </strong>In 1984, Congress enacted legislation authorizing the use of federal funds for Emergency Medical Services for Children, a program to enhance the pediatric capability of existing emergency medical systems. The EMSC program is the only federal grant program specifically focused on addressing the distinct needs of children in prehospital and hospital emergency medical systems. </p>
<p><strong>Current Structure:</strong> <a href="https://emscimprovement.center/impact/">EMSC </a>developed nine performance measures in 2016 to demonstrate the results of program funding given to states/territories. As of 2018, 50 states, Washington D.C., five U.S. territories, and two freely associated states had received new state partnership grants. </p>
<h3><strong>Special Supplemental Food Program for Women, Infants and Children (WIC)</strong></h3>
<p><strong>History: </strong>WIC was created as a two-year pilot program in 1972 by an amendment to the Child Nutrition Act of 1966. It was made permanent in 1975. </p>
<p><strong>Current Structure:</strong> WIC operates through a federal/state/local partnership. <a href="https://www.fns.usda.gov/wic">WIC</a> provides federal grants to states for supplemental foods, health care referrals, and nutrition education for low-income pregnant, breastfeeding, and non-breastfeeding postpartum women, and to infants and children up to age five who are found to be at nutritional risk. USDA&rsquo;s Food and Nutrition Service (FNS) administers the program, which is available in each state, the District of Columbia, 33 Indian Tribal Organizations, Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands, American Samoa, and Guam. FNS issues regulations, monitors compliance, provides technical assistance to state agencies, and conducts studies of program operation and compliance.</p>
<h3>State Title V Programs</h3>
<p>Title V helps create federal/state partnerships that enable each state or jurisdiction to address the health services needs of its mothers, infants and children, including children and youth with special health care needs, and their families. Title V is the biggest driver of positive change for these populations in the country.<sup>2</sup></p>
<p>State maternal and child health agencies, which are usually located within a state health department, apply annually for Title V funding. The legislation also requires states to submit an annual report and to complete a statewide, comprehensive needs assessment every five years. States have flexibility in how Title V funds are used to support a wide range of activities that address state and national needs.</p>
<p>In 2015, the Maternal and Child Health Bureau revised the needs assessment, grant application, and reporting process that states use for the Title V MCH block. This transformation was intended to increase accountability while still maintaining flexibility for states and reducing their reporting burden.<sup>2</sup> </p>
<p>The bureau instituted a three-tiered performance measure framework to enable states to demonstrate the impacts of Title V on selected health outcomes. States apply this new framework in developing a five-year State Action Plan to address their identified MCH priority needs.</p>
